-- Deals of the day- Mergers and acquisitions
-- 
-- Thu Aug 14, 2014 06:31AM EDT
-- None



Aug 14 (Reuters) - The following bids, mergers, acquisitions and disposals were reported by 1030 GMT on Thursday:

** British construction firm Carillion Plc <CLLN.L> is proposing to pay shareholders of its takeover target Balfour Beatty Plc <BALF.L> an additional cash dividend of 8.5 pence per share. Carillion said a merger would save the companies over 1.5 billion pounds ($2.50 billion). [ID:nL4N0QK2QF]  ** French private equity firm Ardian and Chinese conglomerate Fosun International Ltd <0656.HK> said they would withdraw their offer for resort operator Club Mediterranee SA <CMIP.PA>, leaving the way clear for a bid by Italian businessman Andrea Bonomi. [ID:nL6N0QK0Q7]  ** RWE AG <RWEG.DE> does not expect the sale of its oil and gas unit DEA [RWEDE.UL] to an investor group led by Russian billionaire Mikhail Fridman to fail, Chief Executive Peter Terium told journalists on a conference call. [ID:nL6N0QK221]  ** The Austrian government has hired PwC Transaction Services to advise it on the sale of nationalized lender Kommunalkredit [KAFINK.UL]. [ID:nL6N0QK2C7]  ** French telecoms group Orange SA <ORAN.PA> is looking to sell around 9,400 mobile antennas in Spain to cut costs and boost profitability as the sector consolidates, a source familiar with the situation said. [ID:nL6N0QK260]  ** Macau gaming services company Paradise Entertainment Ltd <1180.HK> said on Thursday that it signed a three-year deal with slot machine maker International Game Technology <IGT.N> to expand distribution of gaming systems in North America and Macau. [ID:nH9N0Q402A]  ** Petrovietnam has bid for a stake in Murphy Oil Corp's <MUR.N> Malaysian oil and gas assets, challenging other suitors including Mitsubishi Corp <8508.T> and Indian state oil companies, a person with direct knowledge of the plan said. [ID:nL4N0QK2L7]  ** South Africa's Northam Platinum Ltd <NHMJ.J> said it was looking at buying mines in the strike-hit industry after it made a full-year loss because of a protracted stoppage at its key operations. [ID:nL6N0QK1I7]  ** Colombian electricity company Celsia SA ESP <CEL.CN> will buy stakes in power-generating facilities in Panama and Costa Rica from France's GDF Suez SA <GSZ.PA> for $840 million, Celsia said in a filing with Colombia's financial regulator on Wednesday, marking the first time the company has expanded abroad. [ID:nL2N0QJ2LV]  ** Avago Technologies Ltd <AVGO.O> said it agreed to sell LSI's Axxia Networking Business to chipmaker Intel Corp <INTC.O> for $650 million in cash. [ID:nL4N0QJ6LB]  ** AAC Capital UK is looking to sell kettle safety firm Strix in a deal that could value the company at $500 million and draw interest from other private equity firms and Chinese buyers, three sources familiar with the matter told Reuters. [ID:nL6N0QK206]  ** Hyundai Motor Co's <005380.KS> heir apparent and vice chairman, Chung Eui-sun, sold a 30 percent stake in its advertising affiliate, Innocean, for 300 billion Korean won($293.8 million), Innocean said in regulatory filing. [ID:nL4N0QK39V]  ** TUI AG's <TUIGn.DE> plans for a merger with its London-listed unit TUI Travel Plc <TT.L> are on track, the German company's chief executive said. [ID:nL6N0QK1B1]  ** South Korean steelmaker Posco <005490.KS> said it was in talks to sell its specialty steel unit to SeAH Besteel Corp <001430.KS>. [ID:nL4N0QK2VW]  ** Germany's ThyssenKrupp AG <TKAG.DE> still plans to divest the Terni steel plant in Italy and the VDM alloy unit in the longer run, its finance chief, Guido Kerkhoff, said. [ID:nL6N0QK1K7]  ** South African bullion producer Harmony Gold Mining Co Ltd <HARJ.J> said it was looking for acquisition opportunities elsewhere in Africa and in Papua New Guinea, even as it scales back investment on existing projects. [ID:nL6N0QK0H8]  ** Europe's second-largest fertilizer maker, Poland's Grupa Azoty SA <ATTP.WA>, said on Thursday that it was still planning foreign takeovers. [ID:nL6N0QK0BH]  ** General Electric Co <GE.N> is reportedly in talks with Sweden's Electrolux AB <ELUXb.ST> and Quirky Inc to sell its household appliances unit, Bloomberg reported, citing people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL4N0QK08W]